\title{Pysam}

\taxon{skill}

\meta{description}{"Genomic file toolkit. Read/write SAM/BAM/CRAM alignments, VCF/BCF variants, FASTA/FASTQ sequences, extract regions, calculate coverage, for NGS data processing pipelines."}

\subtree{
\title{Pysam}
\subtree{
\title{Overview}
\p{Pysam is a Python module for reading, manipulating, and writing genomic datasets. Read/write SAM/BAM/CRAM alignment files, VCF/BCF variant files, and FASTA/FASTQ sequences with a Pythonic interface to htslib. Query tabix-indexed files, perform pileup analysis for coverage, and execute samtools/bcftools commands.}
}

\subtree{
\title{When to Use This Skill}
\p{This skill should be used when:}

\ul{
\li{Working with sequencing alignment files (BAM/CRAM)}
\li{Analyzing genetic variants (VCF/BCF)}
\li{Extracting reference sequences or gene regions}
\li{Processing raw sequencing data (FASTQ)}
\li{Calculating coverage or read depth}
\li{Implementing bioinformatics analysis pipelines}
\li{Quality control of sequencing data}
\li{Variant calling and annotation workflows}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Quick Start}
\subtree{
\title{Installation}
\pre{\startverb
uv pip install pysam
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Basic Examples}
\p{\strong{Read alignment file:}}

\pre{\startverb
import pysam

# Open BAM file and fetch reads in region
samfile = pysam.AlignmentFile("example.bam", "rb")
for read in samfile.fetch("chr1", 1000, 2000):
    print(f"{read.query_name}: {read.reference_start}")
samfile.close()
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Read variant file:}}

\pre{\startverb
# Open VCF file and iterate variants
vcf = pysam.VariantFile("variants.vcf")
for variant in vcf:
    print(f"{variant.chrom}:{variant.pos} {variant.ref}>{variant.alts}")
vcf.close()
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Query reference sequence:}}

\pre{\startverb
# Open FASTA and extract sequence
fasta = pysam.FastaFile("reference.fasta")
sequence = fasta.fetch("chr1", 1000, 2000)
print(sequence)
fasta.close()
\stopverb}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Core Capabilities}
\subtree{
\title{1. Alignment File Operations (SAM/BAM/CRAM)}
\p{Use the \code{\startverb AlignmentFile\stopverb} class to work with aligned sequencing reads. This is appropriate for analyzing mapping results, calculating coverage, extracting reads, or quality control.}

\p{\strong{Common operations:}}

\ul{
\li{Open and read BAM/SAM/CRAM files}
\li{Fetch reads from specific genomic regions}
\li{Filter reads by mapping quality, flags, or other criteria}
\li{Write filtered or modified alignments}
\li{Calculate coverage statistics}
\li{Perform pileup analysis (base-by-base coverage)}
\li{Access read sequences, quality scores, and alignment information}
}

\p{\strong{Reference:} See \code{\startverb references/alignment_files.md\stopverb} for detailed documentation on:}

\ul{
\li{Opening and reading alignment files}
\li{AlignedSegment attributes and methods}
\li{Region-based fetching with \code{\startverb fetch()\stopverb}}
\li{Pileup analysis for coverage}
\li{Writing and creating BAM files}
\li{Coordinate systems and indexing}
\li{Performance optimization tips}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{2. Variant File Operations (VCF/BCF)}
\p{Use the \code{\startverb VariantFile\stopverb} class to work with genetic variants from variant calling pipelines. This is appropriate for variant analysis, filtering, annotation, or population genetics.}

\p{\strong{Common operations:}}

\ul{
\li{Read and write VCF/BCF files}
\li{Query variants in specific regions}
\li{Access variant information (position, alleles, quality)}
\li{Extract genotype data for samples}
\li{Filter variants by quality, allele frequency, or other criteria}
\li{Annotate variants with additional information}
\li{Subset samples or regions}
}

\p{\strong{Reference:} See \code{\startverb references/variant_files.md\stopverb} for detailed documentation on:}

\ul{
\li{Opening and reading variant files}
\li{VariantRecord attributes and methods}
\li{Accessing INFO and FORMAT fields}
\li{Working with genotypes and samples}
\li{Creating and writing VCF files}
\li{Filtering and subsetting variants}
\li{Multi-sample VCF operations}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{3. Sequence File Operations (FASTA/FASTQ)}
\p{Use \code{\startverb FastaFile\stopverb} for random access to reference sequences and \code{\startverb FastxFile\stopverb} for reading raw sequencing data. This is appropriate for extracting gene sequences, validating variants against reference, or processing raw reads.}

\p{\strong{Common operations:}}

\ul{
\li{Query reference sequences by genomic coordinates}
\li{Extract sequences for genes or regions of interest}
\li{Read FASTQ files with quality scores}
\li{Validate variant reference alleles}
\li{Calculate sequence statistics}
\li{Filter reads by quality or length}
\li{Convert between FASTA and FASTQ formats}
}

\p{\strong{Reference:} See \code{\startverb references/sequence_files.md\stopverb} for detailed documentation on:}

\ul{
\li{FASTA file access and indexing}
\li{Extracting sequences by region}
\li{Handling reverse complement for genes}
\li{Reading FASTQ files sequentially}
\li{Quality score conversion and filtering}
\li{Working with tabix-indexed files (BED, GTF, GFF)}
\li{Common sequence processing patterns}
}
}

